\begin_layout Standard
Recall from finance 1: the 
\series bold
present value
\series default
 of a project is the sum of the future cash flows, discounted to the present.
 
\series bold
Depreciation
\series default
 - an accounting method of allocating the cost of an asset over its useful
 life.
 
\series bold
Working capital
\series default
 - money that has to be put aside in order to allow business operations
 (cash register, inventory, credit to customers / from suppliers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The revenue minus COGS (cost of goods sold) and depreciation gives 
\series bold
EBIT
\series default
 (earnings before interest & tax).
 After subtracting taxes we get the 
\series bold
NOPAT
\series default
 (net operating income after tax).
 Adding back the depreciation and subtracting the working capital, we finally
 get the 
\series bold
free cash flow
\series default
 (FCF).
\end_layout

